    "design_notes": {
      "power_rails": "This IC has TWO separate power pins with DIFFERENT voltage requirements. VDD (pin 1) = 3.0-3.6V, this is the LOGIC power supply that sets I2C and GPIO voltage levels. VUSB (pin 11) = 4.75-5.25V, this is the USB transceiver power. These are DIFFERENT rails — do NOT swap them.",
      "required_passives": "0.1uF decoupling cap on VDD (pin 1) to GND. 1uF bulk cap on VDD to GND. 0.47uF decoupling cap on VUSB (pin 11) to GND.",
      "reset_pin": "RST (pin 4) is active-low. Connect 10K pull-up resistor from RST to VDD for normal operation.",
      "i2c_bus": "SDA (pin 9) and SCL (pin 10) are open-drain I2C lines. Voltage level is set by VDD. Pull-up resistors (4.7K) should go to VDD (3.3V), NOT to VUSB (5V).",
      "typical_application": "VDD connects to 3.3V rail. VUSB connects to 5V USB power rail. D- (pin 12) and D+ (pin 13) connect to USB connector data lines. SDA and SCL connect to I2C peripherals with 4.7K pull-ups to VDD.",
      "critical_notes": "FATAL ERROR if VDD and VUSB are swapped: putting 5V on VDD will damage the IC or connected I2C devices. Putting 3.3V on VUSB will prevent USB communication. VDD sets I2C voltage levels — if BME280 runs at 3.3V, VDD must be 3.3V."
    }
